  43 @tf_export('keras.layers.StackedRNNCells')
  44 class StackedRNNCells(Layer):
  45   """Wrapper allowing a stack of RNN cells to behave as a single cell.
  46 
  47   Used to implement efficient stacked RNNs.
  48 
  49   Arguments:
  50       cells: List of RNN cell instances.
  51 
  52   Examples:
  53 
  54   ```python
  55       cells = [
  56           keras.layers.LSTMCell(output_dim),
  57           keras.layers.LSTMCell(output_dim),
  58           keras.layers.LSTMCell(output_dim),
  59       ]
  60 
  61       inputs = keras.Input((timesteps, input_dim))
  62       x = keras.layers.RNN(cells)(inputs)
  63   ```
  64   """
  65 
  66   def __init__(self, cells, **kwargs):
  67     for cell in cells:
  68       if not hasattr(cell, 'call'):
  69         raise ValueError('All cells must have a `call` method. '
  70                          'received cells:', cells)
  71       if not hasattr(cell, 'state_size'):
  72         raise ValueError('All cells must have a '
  73                          '`state_size` attribute. '
  74                          'received cells:', cells)
  75     self.cells = cells
  76     # reverse_state_order determines whether the state size will be in a reverse
  77     # order of the cells' state. User might want to set this to True to keep the
  78     # existing behavior. This is only useful when use RNN(return_state=True)
  79     # since the state will be returned as the same order of state_size.
  80     self.reverse_state_order = kwargs.pop('reverse_state_order', False)
  81     if self.reverse_state_order:
  82       logging.warning('reverse_state_order=True in StackedRNNCells will soon '
  83                       'be deprecated. Please update the code to work with the '
  84                       'natural order of states if you reply on the RNN states, '
  85                       'eg RNN(return_state=True).')
  86     super(StackedRNNCells, self).__init__(**kwargs)
  87 
  88   @property
  89   def state_size(self):
  90     # States are a flat list of the individual cell state size.
  91     # e.g. states of a 2-layer LSTM would be `[h1, c1, h2, c2]`.
  92     # (assuming one LSTM has states [h, c])
  93     # In the case of reverse_state_order=True, the state_size will be
  94     # [h2, c2, h1, c1].
  95     state_size = []
  96     for cell in self.cells[::-1] if self.reverse_state_order else self.cells:
  97       if _is_multiple_state(cell.state_size):
  98         state_size += list(cell.state_size)
  99       else:
 100         state_size.append(cell.state_size)
 101     return tuple(state_size)
 102 
 103   @property
 104   def output_size(self):
 105     if getattr(self.cells[-1], 'output_size', None) is not None:
 106       return self.cells[-1].output_size
 107     elif _is_multiple_state(self.cells[-1].state_size):
 108       return self.cells[-1].state_size[0]
 109     else:
 110       return self.cells[-1].state_size
 111 
 112   def get_initial_state(self, inputs=None, batch_size=None, dtype=None):
 113     # The init state is flattened into a list because state_size is a flattened
 114     # list.
 115     initial_states = []
 116     for cell in self.cells[::-1] if self.reverse_state_order else self.cells:
 117       get_initial_state_fn = getattr(cell, 'get_initial_state', None)
 118       if get_initial_state_fn:
 119         initial_states.append(get_initial_state_fn(
 120             inputs=inputs, batch_size=batch_size, dtype=dtype))
 121       else:
 122         initial_states.append(_generate_zero_filled_state_for_cell(
 123             cell, inputs, batch_size, dtype))
 124 
 125     return nest.flatten(initial_states)
 126 
 127   def call(self, inputs, states, constants=None, **kwargs):
 128     # Recover per-cell states.
 129     nested_states = []
 130     for cell in self.cells[::-1] if self.reverse_state_order else self.cells:
 131       if _is_multiple_state(cell.state_size):
 132         nested_states.append(states[:len(cell.state_size)])
 133         states = states[len(cell.state_size):]
 134       else:
 135         nested_states.append([states[0]])
 136         states = states[1:]
 137     if self.reverse_state_order:
 138       nested_states = nested_states[::-1]
 139 
 140     # Call the cells in order and store the returned states.
 141     new_nested_states = []
 142     for cell, states in zip(self.cells, nested_states):
 143       if generic_utils.has_arg(cell.call, 'constants'):
 144         inputs, states = cell.call(inputs, states, constants=constants,
 145                                    **kwargs)
 146       else:
 147         inputs, states = cell.call(inputs, states, **kwargs)
 148 
 149       new_nested_states.append(states)
 150 
 151     # Format the new states as a flat list
 152     new_states = []
 153     if self.reverse_state_order:
 154       new_nested_states = new_nested_states[::-1]
 155     for cell_states in new_nested_states:
 156       new_states += cell_states
 157     return inputs, new_states
 158 
 159   @tf_utils.shape_type_conversion
 160   def build(self, input_shape):
 161     if isinstance(input_shape, list):
 162       constants_shape = input_shape[1:]
 163       input_shape = input_shape[0]
 164     for cell in self.cells:
 165       if isinstance(cell, Layer):
 166         if generic_utils.has_arg(cell.call, 'constants'):
 167           cell.build([input_shape] + constants_shape)
 168         else:
 169           cell.build(input_shape)
 170       if getattr(cell, 'output_size', None) is not None:
 171         output_dim = cell.output_size
 172       elif _is_multiple_state(cell.state_size):
 173         output_dim = cell.state_size[0]
 174       else:
 175         output_dim = cell.state_size
 176       input_shape = tuple([input_shape[0]] +
 177                           tensor_shape.as_shape(output_dim).as_list())
 178     self.built = True
 179 
 180   def get_config(self):
 181     cells = []
 182     for cell in self.cells:
 183       cells.append({
 184           'class_name': cell.__class__.__name__,
 185           'config': cell.get_config()
 186       })
 187     config = {'cells': cells}
 188     base_config = super(StackedRNNCells, self).get_config()
 189     return dict(list(base_config.items()) + list(config.items()))
 190 
 191   @classmethod
 192   def from_config(cls, config, custom_objects=None):
 193     from tensorflow.python.keras.layers import deserialize as deserialize_layer  # pylint: disable=g-import-not-at-top
 194     cells = []
 195     for cell_config in config.pop('cells'):
 196       cells.append(
 197           deserialize_layer(cell_config, custom_objects=custom_objects))
 198     return cls(cells, **config)
 199 
 200   @property
 201   def trainable_weights(self):
 202     if not self.trainable:
 203       return []
 204     weights = []
 205     for cell in self.cells:
 206       if isinstance(cell, Layer):
 207         weights += cell.trainable_weights
 208     return weights
 209 
 210   @property
 211   def non_trainable_weights(self):
 212     weights = []
 213     for cell in self.cells:
 214       if isinstance(cell, Layer):
 215         weights += cell.non_trainable_weights
 216     if not self.trainable:
 217       trainable_weights = []
 218       for cell in self.cells:
 219         if isinstance(cell, Layer):
 220           trainable_weights += cell.trainable_weights
 221       return trainable_weights + weights
 222     return weights
 223 
 224   def get_weights(self):
 225     """Retrieves the weights of the model.
 226 
 227     Returns:
 228         A flat list of Numpy arrays.
 229     """
 230     weights = []
 231     for cell in self.cells:
 232       if isinstance(cell, Layer):
 233         weights += cell.weights
 234     return K.batch_get_value(weights)
 235 
 236   def set_weights(self, weights):
 237     """Sets the weights of the model.
 238 
 239     Arguments:
 240         weights: A list of Numpy arrays with shapes and types matching
 241             the output of `model.get_weights()`.
 242     """
 243     tuples = []
 244     for cell in self.cells:
 245       if isinstance(cell, Layer):
 246         num_param = len(cell.weights)
 247         weights = weights[:num_param]
 248         for sw, w in zip(cell.weights, weights):
 249           tuples.append((sw, w))
 250         weights = weights[num_param:]
 251     K.batch_set_value(tuples)
 252 
 253   @property
 254   def losses(self):
 255     losses = []
 256     for cell in self.cells:
 257       if isinstance(cell, Layer):
 258         losses += cell.losses
 259     return losses + self._losses
 260 
 261   @property
 262   def updates(self):
 263     updates = []
 264     for cell in self.cells:
 265       if isinstance(cell, Layer):
 266         updates += cell.updates
 267     return updates + self._updates

 270 @tf_export('keras.layers.RNN')
 271 class RNN(Layer):
 272   """Base class for recurrent layers.
 273 
 274   Arguments:
 275       cell: A RNN cell instance or a list of RNN cell instances.
 276           A RNN cell is a class that has:
 277           - a `call(input_at_t, states_at_t)` method, returning
 278               `(output_at_t, states_at_t_plus_1)`. The call method of the
 279               cell can also take the optional argument `constants`, see
 280               section "Note on passing external constants" below.
 281           - a `state_size` attribute. This can be a single integer
 282               (single state) in which case it is the size of the recurrent
 283               state. This can also be a list/tuple of integers (one size per
 284               state).
 285               The `state_size` can also be TensorShape or tuple/list of
 286               TensorShape, to represent high dimension state.
 287           - a `output_size` attribute. This can be a single integer or a
 288               TensorShape, which represent the shape of the output. For backward
 289               compatible reason, if this attribute is not available for the
 290               cell, the value will be inferred by the first element of the
 291               `state_size`.
 292           - a `get_initial_state(inputs=None, batch_size=None, dtype=None)`
 293               method that creates a tensor meant to be fed to `call()` as the
 294               initial state, if user didn't specify any initial state via other
 295               means. The returned initial state should be in shape of
 296               [batch, cell.state_size]. Cell might choose to create zero filled
 297               tensor, or with other values based on the cell implementations.
 298               `inputs` is the input tensor to the RNN layer, which should
 299               contain the batch size as its shape[0], and also dtype. Note that
 300               the shape[0] might be None during the graph construction. Either
 301               the `inputs` or the pair of `batch` and `dtype `are provided.
 302               `batch` is a scalar tensor that represent the batch size
 303               of the input. `dtype` is `tf.dtype` that represent the dtype of
 304               the input.
 305               For backward compatible reason, if this method is not implemented
 306               by the cell, RNN layer will create a zero filled tensors with the
 307               size of [batch, cell.state_size].
 308           In the case that `cell` is a list of RNN cell instances, the cells
 309           will be stacked on after the other in the RNN, implementing an
 310           efficient stacked RNN.
 311       return_sequences: Boolean. Whether to return the last output
 312           in the output sequence, or the full sequence.
 313       return_state: Boolean. Whether to return the last state
 314           in addition to the output.
 315       go_backwards: Boolean (default False).
 316           If True, process the input sequence backwards and return the
 317           reversed sequence.
 318       stateful: Boolean (default False). If True, the last state
 319           for each sample at index i in a batch will be used as initial
 320           state for the sample of index i in the following batch.
 321       unroll: Boolean (default False).
 322           If True, the network will be unrolled,
 323           else a symbolic loop will be used.
 324           Unrolling can speed-up a RNN,
 325           although it tends to be more memory-intensive.
 326           Unrolling is only suitable for short sequences.
 327       input_dim: dimensionality of the input (integer or tuple of integers).
 328           This argument (or alternatively, the keyword argument `input_shape`)
 329           is required when using this layer as the first layer in a model.
 330       input_length: Length of input sequences, to be specified
 331           when it is constant.
 332           This argument is required if you are going to connect
 333           `Flatten` then `Dense` layers upstream
 334           (without it, the shape of the dense outputs cannot be computed).
 335           Note that if the recurrent layer is not the first layer
 336           in your model, you would need to specify the input length
 337           at the level of the first layer
 338           (e.g. via the `input_shape` argument)
 339 
 340   Input shape:
 341       N-D tensor with shape `(batch_size, timesteps, ...)`.
 342 
 343   Output shape:
 344       - if `return_state`: a list of tensors. The first tensor is
 345           the output. The remaining tensors are the last states,
 346           each with shape `(batch_size, state_size)`, where `state_size` could
 347           be a high dimension tensor shape.
 348       - if `return_sequences`: N-D tensor with shape
 349           `(batch_size, timesteps, output_size)`, where `output_size` could
 350           be a high dimension tensor shape.
 351       - else, N-D tensor with shape `(batch_size, output_size)`, where
 352           `output_size` could be a high dimension tensor shape.
 353 
 354   # Masking
 355       This layer supports masking for input data with a variable number
 356       of timesteps. To introduce masks to your data,
 357       use an [Embedding](embeddings.md) layer with the `mask_zero` parameter
 358       set to `True`.
 359 
 360   # Note on using statefulness in RNNs
 361       You can set RNN layers to be 'stateful', which means that the states
 362       computed for the samples in one batch will be reused as initial states
 363       for the samples in the next batch. This assumes a one-to-one mapping
 364       between samples in different successive batches.
 365 
 366       To enable statefulness:
 367           - specify `stateful=True` in the layer constructor.
 368           - specify a fixed batch size for your model, by passing
 369               if sequential model:
 370                 `batch_input_shape=(...)` to the first layer in your model.
 371               else for functional model with 1 or more Input layers:
 372                 `batch_shape=(...)` to all the first layers in your model.
 373               This is the expected shape of your inputs
 374               *including the batch size*.
 375               It should be a tuple of integers, e.g. `(32, 10, 100)`.
 376           - specify `shuffle=False` when calling fit().
 377 
 378       To reset the states of your model, call `.reset_states()` on either
 379       a specific layer, or on your entire model.
 380 
 381   # Note on specifying the initial state of RNNs
 382       You can specify the initial state of RNN layers symbolically by
 383       calling them with the keyword argument `initial_state`. The value of
 384       `initial_state` should be a tensor or list of tensors representing
 385       the initial state of the RNN layer.
 386 
 387       You can specify the initial state of RNN layers numerically by
 388       calling `reset_states` with the keyword argument `states`. The value of
 389       `states` should be a numpy array or list of numpy arrays representing
 390       the initial state of the RNN layer.
 391 
 392   # Note on passing external constants to RNNs
 393       You can pass "external" constants to the cell using the `constants`
 394       keyword argument of `RNN.__call__` (as well as `RNN.call`) method. This
 395       requires that the `cell.call` method accepts the same keyword argument
 396       `constants`. Such constants can be used to condition the cell
 397       transformation on additional static inputs (not changing over time),
 398       a.k.a. an attention mechanism.
 399 
 400   Examples:
 401 
 402   ```python
 403       # First, let's define a RNN Cell, as a layer subclass.
 404 
 405       class MinimalRNNCell(keras.layers.Layer):
 406 
 407           def __init__(self, units, **kwargs):
 408               self.units = units
 409               self.state_size = units
 410               super(MinimalRNNCell, self).__init__(**kwargs)
 411 
 412           def build(self, input_shape):
 413               self.kernel = self.add_weight(shape=(input_shape[-1], self.units),
 414                                             initializer='uniform',
 415                                             name='kernel')
 416               self.recurrent_kernel = self.add_weight(
 417                   shape=(self.units, self.units),
 418                   initializer='uniform',
 419                   name='recurrent_kernel')
 420               self.built = True
 421 
 422           def call(self, inputs, states):
 423               prev_output = states[0]
 424               h = K.dot(inputs, self.kernel)
 425               output = h + K.dot(prev_output, self.recurrent_kernel)
 426               return output, [output]
 427 
 428       # Let's use this cell in a RNN layer:
 429 
 430       cell = MinimalRNNCell(32)
 431       x = keras.Input((None, 5))
 432       layer = RNN(cell)
 433       y = layer(x)
 434 
 435       # Here's how to use the cell to build a stacked RNN:
 436 
 437       cells = [MinimalRNNCell(32), MinimalRNNCell(64)]
 438       x = keras.Input((None, 5))
 439       layer = RNN(cells)
 440       y = layer(x)
 441   ```
 442   """
 443 
 444   def __init__(self,
 445                cell,
 446                return_sequences=False,
 447                return_state=False,
 448                go_backwards=False,
 449                stateful=False,
 450                unroll=False,
 451                **kwargs):
 452     if isinstance(cell, (list, tuple)):
 453       cell = StackedRNNCells(cell)
 454     if not hasattr(cell, 'call'):
 455       raise ValueError('`cell` should have a `call` method. '
 456                        'The RNN was passed:', cell)
 457     if not hasattr(cell, 'state_size'):
 458       raise ValueError('The RNN cell should have '
 459                        'an attribute `state_size` '
 460                        '(tuple of integers, '
 461                        'one integer per RNN state).')
 462     super(RNN, self).__init__(**kwargs)
 463     self.cell = cell
 464     if isinstance(cell, checkpointable.CheckpointableBase):
 465       self._track_checkpointable(self.cell, name='cell')
 466     self.return_sequences = return_sequences
 467     self.return_state = return_state
 468     self.go_backwards = go_backwards
 469     self.stateful = stateful
 470     self.unroll = unroll
 471 
 472     self.supports_masking = True
 473     self.input_spec = [None]  # The input shape is unknown yet, at least rank 3.
 474     self.state_spec = None
 475     self._states = None
 476     self.constants_spec = None
 477     self._num_constants = None
 478 
 479   @property
 480   def states(self):
 481     if self._states is None:
 482       state = nest.map_structure(lambda _: None, self.cell.state_size)
 483       return state if nest.is_sequence(self.cell.state_size) else [state]
 484     return self._states
 485 
 486   @states.setter
 487   def states(self, states):
 488     self._states = states
 489 
 490   @tf_utils.shape_type_conversion
 491   def compute_output_shape(self, input_shape):
 492     if isinstance(input_shape, list):
 493       input_shape = input_shape[0]
 494 
 495     if _is_multiple_state(self.cell.state_size):
 496       state_size = self.cell.state_size
 497     else:
 498       state_size = [self.cell.state_size]
 499 
 500     if getattr(self.cell, 'output_size', None) is not None:
 501       output_dim = tensor_shape.as_shape(self.cell.output_size).as_list()
 502     else:
 503       # Note that state_size[0] could be a tensor_shape or int.
 504       output_dim = tensor_shape.as_shape(state_size[0]).as_list()
 505 
 506     if self.return_sequences:
 507       output_shape = tuple([input_shape[0], input_shape[1]] + output_dim)
 508     else:
 509       output_shape = tuple([input_shape[0]] + output_dim)
 510 
 511     if self.return_state:
 512       state_shape = [
 513           tuple([input_shape[0]] + tensor_shape.as_shape(dim).as_list())
 514           for dim in state_size
 515       ]
 516       return [output_shape] + state_shape
 517     else:
 518       return output_shape
 519 
 520   def compute_mask(self, inputs, mask):
 521     if isinstance(mask, list):
 522       mask = mask[0]
 523     output_mask = mask if self.return_sequences else None
 524     if self.return_state:
 525       state_mask = [None for _ in self.states]
 526       return [output_mask] + state_mask
 527     else:
 528       return output_mask
 529 
 530   @tf_utils.shape_type_conversion
 531   def build(self, input_shape):
 532     # Note input_shape will be list of shapes of initial states and
 533     # constants if these are passed in __call__.
 534     if self._num_constants is not None:
 535       constants_shape = input_shape[-self._num_constants:]  # pylint: disable=invalid-unary-operand-type
 536     else:
 537       constants_shape = None
 538 
 539     if isinstance(input_shape, list):
 540       input_shape = input_shape[0]
 541 
 542     batch_size = input_shape[0] if self.stateful else None
 543     input_dim = input_shape[2:]
 544     self.input_spec[0] = InputSpec(shape=(batch_size, None) + input_dim)
 545 
 546     # allow cell (if layer) to build before we set or validate state_spec
 547     if isinstance(self.cell, Layer):
 548       step_input_shape = (input_shape[0],) + input_dim
 549       if constants_shape is not None:
 550         self.cell.build([step_input_shape] + constants_shape)
 551       else:
 552         self.cell.build(step_input_shape)
 553 
 554     # set or validate state_spec
 555     if _is_multiple_state(self.cell.state_size):
 556       state_size = list(self.cell.state_size)
 557     else:
 558       state_size = [self.cell.state_size]
 559 
 560     if self.state_spec is not None:
 561       # initial_state was passed in call, check compatibility
 562       self._validate_state_spec(state_size, self.state_spec)
 563     else:
 564       self.state_spec = [
 565           InputSpec(shape=[None] + tensor_shape.as_shape(dim).as_list())
 566           for dim in state_size
 567       ]
 568     if self.stateful:
 569       self.reset_states()
 570     self.built = True
 571 
 572   @staticmethod
 573   def _validate_state_spec(cell_state_sizes, init_state_specs):
 574     """Validate the state spec between the initial_state and the state_size.
 575 
 576     Args:
 577       cell_state_sizes: list, the `state_size` attribute from the cell.
 578       init_state_specs: list, the `state_spec` from the initial_state that is
 579         passed in call()
 580 
 581     Raises:
 582       ValueError: When initial state spec is not compatible with the state size.
 583     """
 584     validation_error = ValueError(
 585         'An `initial_state` was passed that is not compatible with '
 586         '`cell.state_size`. Received `state_spec`={}; '
 587         'however `cell.state_size` is '
 588         '{}'.format(init_state_specs, cell_state_sizes))
 589     if len(cell_state_sizes) == len(init_state_specs):
 590       for i in range(len(cell_state_sizes)):
 591         if not tensor_shape.TensorShape(
 592             # Ignore the first axis for init_state which is for batch
 593             init_state_specs[i].shape[1:]).is_compatible_with(
 594                 tensor_shape.TensorShape(cell_state_sizes[i])):
 595           raise validation_error
 596     else:
 597       raise validation_error
 598 
 599   def get_initial_state(self, inputs):
 600     get_initial_state_fn = getattr(self.cell, 'get_initial_state', None)
 601     if get_initial_state_fn:
 602       init_state = get_initial_state_fn(
 603           inputs=inputs, batch_size=None, dtype=None)
 604     else:
 605       init_state = _generate_zero_filled_state(
 606           array_ops.shape(inputs)[0], self.cell.state_size, inputs.dtype)
 607     # Keras RNN expect the states in a list, even if it's a single state tensor.
 608     if not nest.is_sequence(init_state):
 609       init_state = [init_state]
 610     # Force the state to be a list in case it is a namedtuple eg LSTMStateTuple.
 611     return list(init_state)
 612 
 613   def __call__(self, inputs, initial_state=None, constants=None, **kwargs):
 614     inputs, initial_state, constants = _standardize_args(inputs,
 615                                                          initial_state,
 616                                                          constants,
 617                                                          self._num_constants)
 618     if initial_state is None and constants is None:
 619       return super(RNN, self).__call__(inputs, **kwargs)
 620 
 621     # If any of `initial_state` or `constants` are specified and are Keras
 622     # tensors, then add them to the inputs and temporarily modify the
 623     # input_spec to include them.
 624 
 625     additional_inputs = []
 626     additional_specs = []
 627     if initial_state is not None:
 628       kwargs['initial_state'] = initial_state
 629       additional_inputs += initial_state
 630       self.state_spec = [
 631           InputSpec(shape=K.int_shape(state)) for state in initial_state
 632       ]
 633       additional_specs += self.state_spec
 634     if constants is not None:
 635       kwargs['constants'] = constants
 636       additional_inputs += constants
 637       self.constants_spec = [
 638           InputSpec(shape=K.int_shape(constant)) for constant in constants
 639       ]
 640       self._num_constants = len(constants)
 641       additional_specs += self.constants_spec
 642     # at this point additional_inputs cannot be empty
 643     is_keras_tensor = K.is_keras_tensor(additional_inputs[0])
 644     for tensor in additional_inputs:
 645       if K.is_keras_tensor(tensor) != is_keras_tensor:
 646         raise ValueError('The initial state or constants of an RNN'
 647                          ' layer cannot be specified with a mix of'
 648                          ' Keras tensors and non-Keras tensors'
 649                          ' (a "Keras tensor" is a tensor that was'
 650                          ' returned by a Keras layer, or by `Input`)')
 651 
 652     if is_keras_tensor:
 653       # Compute the full input spec, including state and constants
 654       full_input = [inputs] + additional_inputs
 655       full_input_spec = self.input_spec + additional_specs
 656       # Perform the call with temporarily replaced input_spec
 657       original_input_spec = self.input_spec
 658       self.input_spec = full_input_spec
 659       output = super(RNN, self).__call__(full_input, **kwargs)
 660       self.input_spec = original_input_spec
 661       return output
 662     else:
 663       return super(RNN, self).__call__(inputs, **kwargs)
 664 
 665   def call(self,
 666            inputs,
 667            mask=None,
 668            training=None,
 669            initial_state=None,
 670            constants=None):
 671     # input shape: `(samples, time (padded with zeros), input_dim)`
 672     # note that the .build() method of subclasses MUST define
 673     # self.input_spec and self.state_spec with complete input shapes.
 674     if isinstance(inputs, list):
 675       # get initial_state from full input spec
 676       # as they could be copied to multiple GPU.
 677       if self._num_constants is None:
 678         initial_state = inputs[1:]
 679       else:
 680         initial_state = inputs[1:-self._num_constants]
 681       if len(initial_state) == 0:
 682         initial_state = None
 683       inputs = inputs[0]
 684     if initial_state is not None:
 685       pass
 686     elif self.stateful:
 687       initial_state = self.states
 688     else:
 689       initial_state = self.get_initial_state(inputs)
 690 
 691     if isinstance(mask, list):
 692       mask = mask[0]
 693 
 694     if len(initial_state) != len(self.states):
 695       raise ValueError(
 696           'Layer has ' + str(len(self.states)) + ' states but was passed ' +
 697           str(len(initial_state)) + ' initial states.')
 698     input_shape = K.int_shape(inputs)
 699     timesteps = input_shape[1]
 700     if self.unroll and timesteps in [None, 1]:
 701       raise ValueError('Cannot unroll a RNN if the '
 702                        'time dimension is undefined or equal to 1. \n'
 703                        '- If using a Sequential model, '
 704                        'specify the time dimension by passing '
 705                        'an `input_shape` or `batch_input_shape` '
 706                        'argument to your first layer. If your '
 707                        'first layer is an Embedding, you can '
 708                        'also use the `input_length` argument.\n'
 709                        '- If using the functional API, specify '
 710                        'the time dimension by passing a `shape` '
 711                        'or `batch_shape` argument to your Input layer.')
 712 
 713     kwargs = {}
 714     if generic_utils.has_arg(self.cell.call, 'training'):
 715       kwargs['training'] = training
 716 
 717     # TF RNN cells expect single tensor as state instead of list wrapped tensor.
 718     is_tf_rnn_cell = getattr(self.cell, '_is_tf_rnn_cell', None) is not None
 719     if constants:
 720       if not generic_utils.has_arg(self.cell.call, 'constants'):
 721         raise ValueError('RNN cell does not support constants')
 722 
 723       def step(inputs, states):
 724         constants = states[-self._num_constants:]  # pylint: disable=invalid-unary-operand-type
 725         states = states[:-self._num_constants]  # pylint: disable=invalid-unary-operand-type
 726 
 727         states = states[0] if len(states) == 1 and is_tf_rnn_cell else states
 728         output, new_states = self.cell.call(
 729             inputs, states, constants=constants, **kwargs)
 730         if not nest.is_sequence(new_states):
 731           new_states = [new_states]
 732         return output, new_states
 733     else:
 734 
 735       def step(inputs, states):
 736         states = states[0] if len(states) == 1 and is_tf_rnn_cell else states
 737         output, new_states = self.cell.call(inputs, states, **kwargs)
 738         if not nest.is_sequence(new_states):
 739           new_states = [new_states]
 740         return output, new_states
 741 
 742     last_output, outputs, states = K.rnn(
 743         step,
 744         inputs,
 745         initial_state,
 746         constants=constants,
 747         go_backwards=self.go_backwards,
 748         mask=mask,
 749         unroll=self.unroll,
 750         input_length=timesteps)
 751     if self.stateful:
 752       updates = []
 753       for i in range(len(states)):
 754         updates.append(state_ops.assign(self.states[i], states[i]))
 755       self.add_update(updates, inputs)
 756 
 757     if self.return_sequences:
 758       output = outputs
 759     else:
 760       output = last_output
 761 
 762     # Properly set learning phase
 763     if getattr(last_output, '_uses_learning_phase', False):
 764       output._uses_learning_phase = True
 765       for state in states:
 766         state._uses_learning_phase = True
 767 
 768     if self.return_state:
 769       if not isinstance(states, (list, tuple)):
 770         states = [states]
 771       else:
 772         states = list(states)
 773       return [output] + states
 774     else:
 775       return output
 776 
 777   def reset_states(self, states=None):
 778     if not self.stateful:
 779       raise AttributeError('Layer must be stateful.')
 780     batch_size = self.input_spec[0].shape[0]
 781     if not batch_size:
 782       raise ValueError('If a RNN is stateful, it needs to know '
 783                        'its batch size. Specify the batch size '
 784                        'of your input tensors: \n'
 785                        '- If using a Sequential model, '
 786                        'specify the batch size by passing '
 787                        'a `batch_input_shape` '
 788                        'argument to your first layer.\n'
 789                        '- If using the functional API, specify '
 790                        'the batch size by passing a '
 791                        '`batch_shape` argument to your Input layer.')
 792     # initialize state if None
 793     if self.states[0] is None:
 794       if _is_multiple_state(self.cell.state_size):
 795         self.states = [
 796             K.zeros([batch_size] + tensor_shape.as_shape(dim).as_list())
 797             for dim in self.cell.state_size
 798         ]
 799       else:
 800         self.states = [
 801             K.zeros([batch_size] +
 802                     tensor_shape.as_shape(self.cell.state_size).as_list())
 803         ]
 804     elif states is None:
 805       if _is_multiple_state(self.cell.state_size):
 806         for state, dim in zip(self.states, self.cell.state_size):
 807           K.set_value(state,
 808                       np.zeros([batch_size] +
 809                                tensor_shape.as_shape(dim).as_list()))
 810       else:
 811         K.set_value(self.states[0], np.zeros(
 812             [batch_size] +
 813             tensor_shape.as_shape(self.cell.state_size).as_list()))
 814     else:
 815       if not isinstance(states, (list, tuple)):
 816         states = [states]
 817       if len(states) != len(self.states):
 818         raise ValueError('Layer ' + self.name + ' expects ' +
 819                          str(len(self.states)) + ' states, '
 820                          'but it received ' + str(len(states)) +
 821                          ' state values. Input received: ' + str(states))
 822       for index, (value, state) in enumerate(zip(states, self.states)):
 823         if _is_multiple_state(self.cell.state_size):
 824           dim = self.cell.state_size[index]
 825         else:
 826           dim = self.cell.state_size
 827         if value.shape != tuple([batch_size] +
 828                                 tensor_shape.as_shape(dim).as_list()):
 829           raise ValueError(
 830               'State ' + str(index) + ' is incompatible with layer ' +
 831               self.name + ': expected shape=' + str(
 832                   (batch_size, dim)) + ', found shape=' + str(value.shape))
 833         # TODO(fchollet): consider batch calls to `set_value`.
 834         K.set_value(state, value)
 835

 837     config = {
 838         'return_sequences': self.return_sequences,
 839         'return_state': self.return_state,
 840         'go_backwards': self.go_backwards,
 841         'stateful': self.stateful,
 842         'unroll': self.unroll
 843     }
 844     if self._num_constants is not None:
 845       config['num_constants'] = self._num_constants
 846

 849         'class_name': self.cell.__class__.__name__,
 850         'config': cell_config

 852     base_config = super(RNN, self).get_config()
 853     return dict(list(base_config.items()) + list(config.items()))

 898 
 899   Arguments:
 900       units: Positive integer, dimensionality of the output space.
 901       activation: Activation function to use.
 902           Default: hyperbolic tangent (`tanh`).

 911       bias_initializer: Initializer for the bias vector.

 914       recurrent_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to
 915           the `recurrent_kernel` weights matrix.
 916       bias_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to the bias vector.
 917       kernel_constraint: Constraint function applied to
 918           the `kernel` weights matrix.
 919       recurrent_constraint: Constraint function applied to
 920           the `recurrent_kernel` weights matrix.
 921       bias_constraint: Constraint function applied to the bias vector.
 922       dropout: Float between 0 and 1.
 923           Fraction of the units to drop for
 924           the linear transformation of the inputs.
 925       recurrent_dropout: Float between 0 and 1.
 926           Fraction of the units to drop for
 927           the linear transformation of the recurrent state.

 930   def __init__(self,
 931                units,
 932                activation='tanh',
 933                use_bias=True,
 934                kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform',
 935                recurrent_initializer='orthogonal',
 936                bias_initializer='zeros',
 937                kernel_regularizer=None,
 938                recurrent_regularizer=None,
 939                bias_regularizer=None,
 940                kernel_constraint=None,
 941                recurrent_constraint=None,
 942                bias_constraint=None,

 944                recurrent_dropout=0.,
 945                **kwargs):
 946     super(SimpleRNNCell, self).__init__(**kwargs)
 947     self.units = units
 948     self.activation = activations.get(activation)
 949     self.use_bias = use_bias
 950 
 951     self.kernel_initializer = initializers.get(kernel_initializer)
 952     self.recurrent_initializer = initializers.get(recurrent_initializer)
 953     self.bias_initializer = initializers.get(bias_initializer)
 954 
 955     self.kernel_regularizer = regularizers.get(kernel_regularizer)
 956     self.recurrent_regularizer = regularizers.get(recurrent_regularizer)
 957     self.bias_regularizer = regularizers.get(bias_regularizer)
 958

 960     self.recurrent_constraint = constraints.get(recurrent_constraint)
 961     self.bias_constraint = constraints.get(bias_constraint)
 962 
 963     self.dropout = min(1., max(0., dropout))
 964     self.recurrent_dropout = min(1., max(0., recurrent_dropout))

 968     self._recurrent_dropout_mask = None

 970   @tf_utils.shape_type_conversion
 971   def build(self, input_shape):
 972     self.kernel = self.add_weight(
 973         shape=(input_shape[-1], self.units),
 974         name='kernel',
 975         initializer=self.kernel_initializer,
 976         regularizer=self.kernel_regularizer,
 977         constraint=self.kernel_constraint)
 978     self.recurrent_kernel = self.add_weight(
 979         shape=(self.units, self.units),
 980         name='recurrent_kernel',
 981         initializer=self.recurrent_initializer,
 982         regularizer=self.recurrent_regularizer,
 983         constraint=self.recurrent_constraint)
 984     if self.use_bias:
 985       self.bias = self.add_weight(
 986           shape=(self.units,),
 987           name='bias',
 988           initializer=self.bias_initializer,
 989           regularizer=self.bias_regularizer,
 990           constraint=self.bias_constraint)
 991     else:
 992       self.bias = None
 993     self.built = True
 994 
 995   def call(self, inputs, states, training=None):
 996     prev_output = states[0]
 997     if 0 < self.dropout < 1 and self._dropout_mask is None:
 998       self._dropout_mask = _generate_dropout_mask(
 999           array_ops.ones_like(inputs),
1000           self.dropout,
1001           training=training)
1002     if (0 < self.recurrent_dropout < 1 and
1003         self._recurrent_dropout_mask is None):
1004       self._recurrent_dropout_mask = _generate_dropout_mask(
1005           array_ops.ones_like(prev_output),
1006           self.recurrent_dropout,
1007           training=training)
1008 
1009     dp_mask = self._dropout_mask
1010     rec_dp_mask = self._recurrent_dropout_mask
1011 
1012     if dp_mask is not None:
1013       h = K.dot(inputs * dp_mask, self.kernel)
1014     else:
1015       h = K.dot(inputs, self.kernel)
1016     if self.bias is not None:
1017       h = K.bias_add(h, self.bias)
1018 
1019     if rec_dp_mask is not None:
1020       prev_output *= rec_dp_mask
1021     output = h + K.dot(prev_output, self.recurrent_kernel)
1022     if self.activation is not None:
1023       output = self.activation(output)
1024 
1025     # Properly set learning phase on output tensor.
1026     if 0 < self.dropout + self.recurrent_dropout:
1027       if training is None and not context.executing_eagerly():
1028         # This would be harmless to set in eager mode, but eager tensors
1029         # disallow setting arbitrary attributes.
1030         output._uses_learning_phase = True
1031     return output, [output]

1282 @tf_export('keras.layers.GRUCell')
1283 class GRUCell(Layer):
1284   """Cell class for the GRU layer.
1285 
1286   Arguments:
1287       units: Positive integer, dimensionality of the output space.
1288       activation: Activation function to use.
1289           Default: hyperbolic tangent (`tanh`).
1290           If you pass None, no activation is applied
1291           (ie. "linear" activation: `a(x) = x`).
1292       recurrent_activation: Activation function to use
1293           for the recurrent step.
1294           Default: hard sigmoid (`hard_sigmoid`).
1295           If you pass `None`, no activation is applied
1296           (ie. "linear" activation: `a(x) = x`).
1297       use_bias: Boolean, whether the layer uses a bias vector.
1298       kernel_initializer: Initializer for the `kernel` weights matrix,
1299           used for the linear transformation of the inputs.
1300       recurrent_initializer: Initializer for the `recurrent_kernel`
1301           weights matrix,
1302           used for the linear transformation of the recurrent state.
1303       bias_initializer: Initializer for the bias vector.
1304       kernel_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to
1305           the `kernel` weights matrix.
1306       recurrent_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to
1307           the `recurrent_kernel` weights matrix.
1308       bias_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to the bias vector.
1309       kernel_constraint: Constraint function applied to
1310           the `kernel` weights matrix.
1311       recurrent_constraint: Constraint function applied to
1312           the `recurrent_kernel` weights matrix.
1313       bias_constraint: Constraint function applied to the bias vector.
1314       dropout: Float between 0 and 1.
1315           Fraction of the units to drop for
1316           the linear transformation of the inputs.
1317       recurrent_dropout: Float between 0 and 1.
1318           Fraction of the units to drop for
1319           the linear transformation of the recurrent state.
1320       implementation: Implementation mode, either 1 or 2.
1321           Mode 1 will structure its operations as a larger number of
1322           smaller dot products and additions, whereas mode 2 will
1323           batch them into fewer, larger operations. These modes will
1324           have different performance profiles on different hardware and
1325           for different applications.
1326       reset_after: GRU convention (whether to apply reset gate after or
1327           before matrix multiplication). False = "before" (default),
1328           True = "after" (CuDNN compatible).
1329   """
1330 
1331   def __init__(self,
1332                units,
1333                activation='tanh',
1334                recurrent_activation='hard_sigmoid',
1335                use_bias=True,
1336                kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform',
1337                recurrent_initializer='orthogonal',
1338                bias_initializer='zeros',
1339                kernel_regularizer=None,
1340                recurrent_regularizer=None,
1341                bias_regularizer=None,
1342                kernel_constraint=None,
1343                recurrent_constraint=None,
1344                bias_constraint=None,
1345                dropout=0.,
1346                recurrent_dropout=0.,
1347                implementation=1,
1348                reset_after=False,
1349                **kwargs):

1351     self.units = units
1352     self.activation = activations.get(activation)
1353     self.recurrent_activation = activations.get(recurrent_activation)
1354     self.use_bias = use_bias
1355 
1356     self.kernel_initializer = initializers.get(kernel_initializer)
1357     self.recurrent_initializer = initializers.get(recurrent_initializer)
1358     self.bias_initializer = initializers.get(bias_initializer)
1359 
1360     self.kernel_regularizer = regularizers.get(kernel_regularizer)
1361     self.recurrent_regularizer = regularizers.get(recurrent_regularizer)
1362     self.bias_regularizer = regularizers.get(bias_regularizer)
1363 
1364     self.kernel_constraint = constraints.get(kernel_constraint)
1365     self.recurrent_constraint = constraints.get(recurrent_constraint)
1366     self.bias_constraint = constraints.get(bias_constraint)
1367 
1368     self.dropout = min(1., max(0., dropout))
1369     self.recurrent_dropout = min(1., max(0., recurrent_dropout))
1370     self.implementation = implementation
1371     self.reset_after = reset_after

1373     self.output_size = self.units

1377   @tf_utils.shape_type_conversion
1378   def build(self, input_shape):
1379     input_dim = input_shape[-1]
1380     self.kernel = self.add_weight(
1381         shape=(input_dim, self.units * 3),
1382         name='kernel',
1383         initializer=self.kernel_initializer,
1384         regularizer=self.kernel_regularizer,
1385         constraint=self.kernel_constraint)
1386     self.recurrent_kernel = self.add_weight(
1387         shape=(self.units, self.units * 3),
1388         name='recurrent_kernel',
1389         initializer=self.recurrent_initializer,
1390         regularizer=self.recurrent_regularizer,
1391         constraint=self.recurrent_constraint)
1392 
1393     if self.use_bias:
1394       if not self.reset_after:
1395         bias_shape = (3 * self.units,)
1396       else:
1397         # separate biases for input and recurrent kernels
1398         # Note: the shape is intentionally different from CuDNNGRU biases
1399         # `(2 * 3 * self.units,)`, so that we can distinguish the classes
1400         # when loading and converting saved weights.
1401         bias_shape = (2, 3 * self.units)
1402       self.bias = self.add_weight(shape=bias_shape,
1403                                   name='bias',
1404                                   initializer=self.bias_initializer,
1405                                   regularizer=self.bias_regularizer,
1406                                   constraint=self.bias_constraint)
1407       if not self.reset_after:
1408         self.input_bias, self.recurrent_bias = self.bias, None
1409       else:
1410         self.input_bias = K.flatten(self.bias[0])
1411         self.recurrent_bias = K.flatten(self.bias[1])
1412 
1413     else:
1414       self.bias = None
1415     self.built = True
1416 
1417   def call(self, inputs, states, training=None):
1418     h_tm1 = states[0]  # previous memory
1419 
1420     if 0 < self.dropout < 1 and self._dropout_mask is None:
1421       self._dropout_mask = _generate_dropout_mask(
1422           array_ops.ones_like(inputs),
1423           self.dropout,
1424           training=training,
1425           count=3)
1426     if (0 < self.recurrent_dropout < 1 and
1427         self._recurrent_dropout_mask is None):
1428       self._recurrent_dropout_mask = _generate_dropout_mask(
1429           array_ops.ones_like(h_tm1),
1430           self.recurrent_dropout,
1431           training=training,
1432           count=3)
1433 
1434     # dropout matrices for input units
1435     dp_mask = self._dropout_mask
1436     # dropout matrices for recurrent units
1437     rec_dp_mask = self._recurrent_dropout_mask
1438 
1439     if self.implementation == 1:
1440       if 0. < self.dropout < 1.:
1441         inputs_z = inputs * dp_mask[0]
1442         inputs_r = inputs * dp_mask[1]
1443         inputs_h = inputs * dp_mask[2]
1444       else:
1445         inputs_z = inputs
1446         inputs_r = inputs
1447         inputs_h = inputs
1448 
1449       x_z = K.dot(inputs_z, self.kernel[:, :self.units])
1450       x_r = K.dot(inputs_r, self.kernel[:, self.units:self.units * 2])
1451       x_h = K.dot(inputs_h, self.kernel[:, self.units * 2:])
1452 
1453       if self.use_bias:
1454         x_z = K.bias_add(x_z, self.input_bias[:self.units])
1455         x_r = K.bias_add(x_r, self.input_bias[self.units: self.units * 2])
1456         x_h = K.bias_add(x_h, self.input_bias[self.units * 2:])
1457 
1458       if 0. < self.recurrent_dropout < 1.:
1459         h_tm1_z = h_tm1 * rec_dp_mask[0]
1460         h_tm1_r = h_tm1 * rec_dp_mask[1]
1461         h_tm1_h = h_tm1 * rec_dp_mask[2]
1462       else:
1463         h_tm1_z = h_tm1
1464         h_tm1_r = h_tm1
1465         h_tm1_h = h_tm1
1466 
1467       recurrent_z = K.dot(h_tm1_z, self.recurrent_kernel[:, :self.units])
1468       recurrent_r = K.dot(h_tm1_r,
1469                           self.recurrent_kernel[:, self.units:self.units * 2])
1470       if self.reset_after and self.use_bias:
1471         recurrent_z = K.bias_add(recurrent_z, self.recurrent_bias[:self.units])
1472         recurrent_r = K.bias_add(recurrent_r,
1473                                  self.recurrent_bias[self.units:
1474                                                      self.units * 2])
1475 
1476       z = self.recurrent_activation(x_z + recurrent_z)
1477       r = self.recurrent_activation(x_r + recurrent_r)
1478 
1479       # reset gate applied after/before matrix multiplication
1480       if self.reset_after:
1481         recurrent_h = K.dot(h_tm1_h, self.recurrent_kernel[:, self.units * 2:])
1482         if self.use_bias:
1483           recurrent_h = K.bias_add(recurrent_h,
1484                                    self.recurrent_bias[self.units * 2:])
1485         recurrent_h = r * recurrent_h
1486       else:
1487         recurrent_h = K.dot(r * h_tm1_h,
1488                             self.recurrent_kernel[:, self.units * 2:])
1489 
1490       hh = self.activation(x_h + recurrent_h)
1491     else:
1492       if 0. < self.dropout < 1.:
1493         inputs *= dp_mask[0]
1494 
1495       # inputs projected by all gate matrices at once
1496       matrix_x = K.dot(inputs, self.kernel)
1497       if self.use_bias:
1498         # biases: bias_z_i, bias_r_i, bias_h_i
1499         matrix_x = K.bias_add(matrix_x, self.input_bias)
1500 
1501       x_z = matrix_x[:, :self.units]
1502       x_r = matrix_x[:, self.units: 2 * self.units]
1503       x_h = matrix_x[:, 2 * self.units:]
1504 
1505       if 0. < self.recurrent_dropout < 1.:
1506         h_tm1 *= rec_dp_mask[0]
1507 
1508       if self.reset_after:
1509         # hidden state projected by all gate matrices at once
1510         matrix_inner = K.dot(h_tm1, self.recurrent_kernel)
1511         if self.use_bias:
1512           matrix_inner = K.bias_add(matrix_inner, self.recurrent_bias)
1513       else:
1514         # hidden state projected separately for update/reset and new
1515         matrix_inner = K.dot(h_tm1, self.recurrent_kernel[:, :2 * self.units])
1516 
1517       recurrent_z = matrix_inner[:, :self.units]
1518       recurrent_r = matrix_inner[:, self.units:2 * self.units]
1519 
1520       z = self.recurrent_activation(x_z + recurrent_z)
1521       r = self.recurrent_activation(x_r + recurrent_r)
1522 
1523       if self.reset_after:
1524         recurrent_h = r * matrix_inner[:, 2 * self.units:]
1525       else:
1526         recurrent_h = K.dot(r * h_tm1,
1527                             self.recurrent_kernel[:, 2 * self.units:])
1528 
1529       hh = self.activation(x_h + recurrent_h)
1530     # previous and candidate state mixed by update gate
1531     h = z * h_tm1 + (1 - z) * hh
1532     if 0 < self.dropout + self.recurrent_dropout:
1533       if training is None and not context.executing_eagerly():
1534         # This would be harmless to set in eager mode, but eager tensors
1535         # disallow setting arbitrary attributes.
1536         h._uses_learning_phase = True
1537 
1538     return h, [h]

1548         'recurrent_initializer':
1549             initializers.serialize(self.recurrent_initializer),
1550         'bias_initializer': initializers.serialize(self.bias_initializer),
1551         'kernel_regularizer': regularizers.serialize(self.kernel_regularizer),
1552         'recurrent_regularizer':
1553             regularizers.serialize(self.recurrent_regularizer),

1571 @tf_export('keras.layers.GRU')
1572 class GRU(RNN):
1573   """Gated Recurrent Unit - Cho et al. 2014.
1574 
1575   There are two variants. The default one is based on 1406.1078v3 and
1576   has reset gate applied to hidden state before matrix multiplication. The
1577   other one is based on original 1406.1078v1 and has the order reversed.
1578 
1579   The second variant is compatible with CuDNNGRU (GPU-only) and allows
1580   inference on CPU. Thus it has separate biases for `kernel` and
1581   `recurrent_kernel`. Use `'reset_after'=True` and
1582   `recurrent_activation='sigmoid'`.
1583 
1584   Arguments:
1585       units: Positive integer, dimensionality of the output space.
1586       activation: Activation function to use.
1587           Default: hyperbolic tangent (`tanh`).
1588           If you pass `None`, no activation is applied
1589           (ie. "linear" activation: `a(x) = x`).
1590       recurrent_activation: Activation function to use
1591           for the recurrent step.
1592           Default: hard sigmoid (`hard_sigmoid`).
1593           If you pass `None`, no activation is applied
1594           (ie. "linear" activation: `a(x) = x`).
1595       use_bias: Boolean, whether the layer uses a bias vector.
1596       kernel_initializer: Initializer for the `kernel` weights matrix,
1597           used for the linear transformation of the inputs.
1598       recurrent_initializer: Initializer for the `recurrent_kernel`
1599           weights matrix,
1600           used for the linear transformation of the recurrent state.
1601       bias_initializer: Initializer for the bias vector.
1602       kernel_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to
1603           the `kernel` weights matrix.
1604       recurrent_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to
1605           the `recurrent_kernel` weights matrix.
1606       bias_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to the bias vector.
1607       activity_regularizer: Regularizer function applied to
1608           the output of the layer (its "activation")..
1609       kernel_constraint: Constraint function applied to
1610           the `kernel` weights matrix.
1611       recurrent_constraint: Constraint function applied to
1612           the `recurrent_kernel` weights matrix.
1613       bias_constraint: Constraint function applied to the bias vector.
1614       dropout: Float between 0 and 1.
1615           Fraction of the units to drop for
1616           the linear transformation of the inputs.
1617       recurrent_dropout: Float between 0 and 1.
1618           Fraction of the units to drop for
1619           the linear transformation of the recurrent state.
1620       implementation: Implementation mode, either 1 or 2.
1621           Mode 1 will structure its operations as a larger number of
1622           smaller dot products and additions, whereas mode 2 will
1623           batch them into fewer, larger operations. These modes will
1624           have different performance profiles on different hardware and
1625           for different applications.
1626       return_sequences: Boolean. Whether to return the last output
1627           in the output sequence, or the full sequence.
1628       return_state: Boolean. Whether to return the last state
1629           in addition to the output.
1630       go_backwards: Boolean (default False).
1631           If True, process the input sequence backwards and return the
1632           reversed sequence.
1633       stateful: Boolean (default False). If True, the last state
1634           for each sample at index i in a batch will be used as initial
1635           state for the sample of index i in the following batch.
1636       unroll: Boolean (default False).
1637           If True, the network will be unrolled,
1638           else a symbolic loop will be used.
1639           Unrolling can speed-up a RNN,
1640           although it tends to be more memory-intensive.
1641           Unrolling is only suitable for short sequences.
1642       reset_after: GRU convention (whether to apply reset gate after or
1643           before matrix multiplication). False = "before" (default),
1644           True = "after" (CuDNN compatible).
1645 
1646   """
1647

1649                units,
1650                activation='tanh',

1653                kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform',
1654                recurrent_initializer='orthogonal',
1655                bias_initializer='zeros',
1656                kernel_regularizer=None,
1657                recurrent_regularizer=None,
1658                bias_regularizer=None,
1659                activity_regularizer=None,
1660                kernel_constraint=None,
1661                recurrent_constraint=None,
1662                bias_constraint=None,
1663                dropout=0.,
1664                recurrent_dropout=0.,

1931         name='kernel',

1946           return K.concatenate([
1947               self.bias_initializer((self.units,), *args, **kwargs),
1948               initializers.Ones()((self.units,), *args, **kwargs),
1949               self.bias_initializer((self.units * 2,), *args, **kwargs),
1950           ])

1953       self.bias = self.add_weight(

1963   def call(self, inputs, states, training=None):
1964     if 0 < self.dropout < 1 and self._dropout_mask is None:
1965       self._dropout_mask = _generate_dropout_mask(
1966           array_ops.ones_like(inputs),
1967           self.dropout,
1968           training=training,
1969           count=4)
1970     if (0 < self.recurrent_dropout < 1 and
1971         self._recurrent_dropout_mask is None):
1972       self._recurrent_dropout_mask = _generate_dropout_mask(
1973           array_ops.ones_like(states[0]),
1974           self.recurrent_dropout,
1975           training=training,
1976           count=4)
1977 
1978     # dropout matrices for input units
1979     dp_mask = self._dropout_mask
1980     # dropout matrices for recurrent units
1981     rec_dp_mask = self._recurrent_dropout_mask
1982 
1983     h_tm1 = states[0]  # previous memory state
1984     c_tm1 = states[1]  # previous carry state
1985 
1986     if self.implementation == 1:
1987       if 0 < self.dropout < 1.:
1988         inputs_i = inputs * dp_mask[0]
1989         inputs_f = inputs * dp_mask[1]
1990         inputs_c = inputs * dp_mask[2]
1991         inputs_o = inputs * dp_mask[3]
1992       else:
1993         inputs_i = inputs
1994         inputs_f = inputs
1995         inputs_c = inputs
1996         inputs_o = inputs
1997       x_i = K.dot(inputs_i, self.kernel[:, :self.units])
1998       x_f = K.dot(inputs_f, self.kernel[:, self.units:self.units * 2])
1999       x_c = K.dot(inputs_c, self.kernel[:, self.units * 2:self.units * 3])
2000       x_o = K.dot(inputs_o, self.kernel[:, self.units * 3:])
2001       if self.use_bias:
2002         x_i = K.bias_add(x_i, self.bias[:self.units])
2003         x_f = K.bias_add(x_f, self.bias[self.units:self.units * 2])
2004         x_c = K.bias_add(x_c, self.bias[self.units * 2:self.units * 3])
2005         x_o = K.bias_add(x_o, self.bias[self.units * 3:])
2006 
2007       if 0 < self.recurrent_dropout < 1.:
2008         h_tm1_i = h_tm1 * rec_dp_mask[0]
2009         h_tm1_f = h_tm1 * rec_dp_mask[1]
2010         h_tm1_c = h_tm1 * rec_dp_mask[2]
2011         h_tm1_o = h_tm1 * rec_dp_mask[3]
2012       else:
2013         h_tm1_i = h_tm1
2014         h_tm1_f = h_tm1
2015         h_tm1_c = h_tm1
2016         h_tm1_o = h_tm1
2017       i = self.recurrent_activation(
2018           x_i + K.dot(h_tm1_i, self.recurrent_kernel[:, :self.units]))
2019       f = self.recurrent_activation(
2020           x_f + K.dot(h_tm1_f,
2021                       self.recurrent_kernel[:, self.units: self.units * 2]))
2022       c = f * c_tm1 + i * self.activation(
2023           x_c + K.dot(h_tm1_c,
2024                       self.recurrent_kernel[:, self.units * 2: self.units * 3]))
2025       o = self.recurrent_activation(
2026           x_o + K.dot(h_tm1_o, self.recurrent_kernel[:, self.units * 3:]))
2027     else:
2028       if 0. < self.dropout < 1.:
2029         inputs *= dp_mask[0]
2030       z = K.dot(inputs, self.kernel)
2031       if 0. < self.recurrent_dropout < 1.:
2032         h_tm1 *= rec_dp_mask[0]
2033       z += K.dot(h_tm1, self.recurrent_kernel)
2034       if self.use_bias:
2035         z = K.bias_add(z, self.bias)
2036 
2037       z0 = z[:, :self.units]
2038       z1 = z[:, self.units:2 * self.units]
2039       z2 = z[:, 2 * self.units:3 * self.units]
2040       z3 = z[:, 3 * self.units:]
2041 
2042       i = self.recurrent_activation(z0)
2043       f = self.recurrent_activation(z1)
2044       c = f * c_tm1 + i * self.activation(z2)
2045       o = self.recurrent_activation(z3)
2046 
2047     h = o * self.activation(c)
2048     if 0 < self.dropout + self.recurrent_dropout:
2049       if training is None and not context.executing_eagerly():
2050         # This would be harmless to set in eager mode, but eager tensors
2051         # disallow setting arbitrary attributes.
2052         h._uses_learning_phase = True
2053     return h, [h, c]

2371 
2372   When running a model loaded from a file, the input tensors
2373   `initial_state` and `constants` can be passed to `RNN.__call__()` as part
2374   of `inputs` instead of by the dedicated keyword arguments. This method
2375   makes sure the arguments are separated and that `initial_state` and
2376   `constants` are lists of tensors (or None).
2377 
2378   Arguments:
2379       inputs: Tensor or list/tuple of tensors. which may include constants
2380         and initial states. In that case `num_constant` must be specified.
2381       initial_state: Tensor or list of tensors or None, initial states.
2382       constants: Tensor or list of tensors or None, constant tensors.
2383       num_constants: Expected number of constants (if constants are passed as
2384         part of the `inputs` list.
2385 
2386   Returns:
2387       inputs: Single tensor.
2388       initial_state: List of tensors or None.
2389       constants: List of tensors or None.
2390   """
2391   if isinstance(inputs, list):
2392     assert initial_state is None and constants is None
2393     if num_constants is not None:
2394       constants = inputs[-num_constants:]
2395       inputs = inputs[:-num_constants]
2396     if len(inputs) > 1:
2397       initial_state = inputs[1:]
2398     inputs = inputs[0]
2399 
2400   def to_list_or_none(x):
2401     if x is None or isinstance(x, list):
2402       return x
2403     if isinstance(x, tuple):
2404       return list(x)
2405     return [x]
2406 
2407   initial_state = to_list_or_none(initial_state)
2408   constants = to_list_or_none(constants)
2409 
2410   return inputs, initial_state, constants
2411

2413 def _is_multiple_state(state_size):
2414   """Check whether the state_size contains multiple states."""
2415   return (hasattr(state_size, '__len__') and
2416           not isinstance(state_size, tensor_shape.TensorShape))

2419 def _generate_zero_filled_state_for_cell(cell, inputs, batch_size, dtype):
2420   if inputs is not None:
2421     batch_size = array_ops.shape(inputs)[0]
2422     dtype = inputs.dtype
2423   return _generate_zero_filled_state(batch_size, cell.state_size, dtype)
2424 
2425 
2426 def _generate_zero_filled_state(batch_size_tensor, state_size, dtype):
2427   """Generate a zero filled tensor with shape [batch_size, state_size]."""
2428   if None in [batch_size_tensor, dtype]:
2429     raise ValueError(
2430         'batch_size and dtype cannot be None while constructing initial state: '
2431         'batch_size={}, dtype={}'.format(batch_size_tensor, dtype))
2432   if _is_multiple_state(state_size):
2433     states = []
2434     for dims in state_size:
2435       flat_dims = tensor_shape.as_shape(dims).as_list()
2436       init_state_size = [batch_size_tensor] + flat_dims
2437       init_state = array_ops.zeros(init_state_size, dtype=dtype)
2438       states.append(init_state)
2439     return states
2440   else:
2441     flat_dims = tensor_shape.as_shape(state_size).as_list()
2442     init_state_size = [batch_size_tensor] + flat_dims
2443     return array_ops.zeros(init_state_size, dtype=dtype)
